WEBVTT

00:00:00.500 --> 00:00:04.120
So, I have a list of things about him.

00:00:10.520 --> 00:00:12.520
Many, many things that are not on this list, including,

00:00:12.520 --> 00:00:13.880
but we narrowed it down to just something.

00:00:13.880 --> 00:00:18.879
So, a little backstory, I've known this guy for 15?

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:21.959
No, many, many, many, many years, many years.

00:00:21.959 --> 00:00:23.879
He was originally a student in one of my classes,

00:00:23.879 --> 00:00:25.320
and he has been a speaker

00:00:25.320 --> 00:00:27.639
at every single one of these conferences.

00:00:27.639 --> 00:00:30.600
Last year, he was in Barcelona during the conference,

00:00:30.600 --> 00:00:31.719
but we had him do a video call

00:00:31.719 --> 00:00:34.000
and so he could keep his streak alive, right?

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:35.919
That's how much we appreciate this guy.

00:00:35.919 --> 00:00:37.939
But, he's becoming Canadian,

00:00:38.799 --> 00:00:40.919
and he has moved to British Columbia, to Vancouver,

00:00:40.919 --> 00:00:43.560
to be a professor, and he's only a permanent resident,

00:00:43.560 --> 00:00:44.560
he's not a citizen yet.

00:00:44.560 --> 00:00:45.540
But to help him on his way,

00:00:45.540 --> 00:00:48.279
he has started watching more hockey, he said.

00:00:48.279 --> 00:00:53.279
He has taken up curling, he drinks Tim Hortons daily,

00:00:54.279 --> 00:00:59.279
he is, oh, his partner likes the Oilers,

00:00:59.759 --> 00:01:00.919
but he's still a sort of Rangers fan

00:01:00.919 --> 00:01:02.480
because he's a through and through New Yorker,

00:01:02.480 --> 00:01:03.959
so that's causing a bit of strife for him.

00:01:03.959 --> 00:01:07.400
And he's even started putting maple syrup in his coffee.

00:01:07.400 --> 00:01:09.400
So, everyone please welcome Dan.

00:01:09.400 --> 00:01:13.480
All right, so, by a show of hands,

00:01:13.480 --> 00:01:16.519
how many of you are still really skeptical

00:01:16.519 --> 00:01:19.599
about using LLMs, anyone?

00:01:19.599 --> 00:01:22.500
Oh, that's actually a lot more than I expected.

00:01:22.500 --> 00:01:24.779
What about just regular skeptical?

00:01:26.260 --> 00:01:28.739
Yeah, okay, cool, everyone else?

00:01:28.739 --> 00:01:30.500
Neutral-ish?

00:01:31.860 --> 00:01:33.000
Promising?

00:01:35.739 --> 00:01:36.779
All the hype?

00:01:37.980 --> 00:01:38.820
All right, cool.

00:01:40.260 --> 00:01:41.820
All right.

00:01:41.820 --> 00:01:43.540
Well, today I kind of wanted to make sure

00:01:43.540 --> 00:01:46.300
that we can get a good solid foundation

00:01:46.300 --> 00:01:48.820
on sort of just moving that curve up just a little bit.

00:01:48.820 --> 00:01:51.260
And you can tell me at the end

00:01:51.260 --> 00:01:52.900
if I've done a good job or not.

00:01:54.260 --> 00:01:56.860
But, yes, we've all heard stories

00:01:56.860 --> 00:01:59.720
about LLMs doing hallucinations.

00:01:59.720 --> 00:02:02.860
This is an example of a research paper

00:02:02.860 --> 00:02:05.699
that they gave an LLM the ability

00:02:05.699 --> 00:02:07.980
to run a vending machine company,

00:02:07.980 --> 00:02:10.220
and then over the course of time,

00:02:10.220 --> 00:02:12.059
thank God it was an air gap system,

00:02:12.059 --> 00:02:14.339
it ended up wanting to call the FBI

00:02:14.339 --> 00:02:16.740
on Cybercrimes Division on the owner

00:02:16.740 --> 00:02:18.979
of this vending machine company

00:02:18.979 --> 00:02:21.979
because someone wasn't paying the stocking fee

00:02:21.979 --> 00:02:23.119
or something like that.

00:02:23.119 --> 00:02:26.419
So these things can go horribly awry.

00:02:27.899 --> 00:02:30.520
Other things that it can do,

00:02:30.520 --> 00:02:32.740
this is literally a night or two ago,

00:02:32.740 --> 00:02:36.179
I asked it to draw an intricate piece of ASCII art,

00:02:36.179 --> 00:02:40.300
and it said, here's a majestic dragon,

00:02:40.300 --> 00:02:41.639
in which case my sister said,

00:02:41.639 --> 00:02:43.179
no, that's a very nervous piglet,

00:02:43.179 --> 00:02:44.220
and now we need a poo sweater.

00:02:44.220 --> 00:02:46.479
So clearly not very good,

00:02:46.479 --> 00:02:49.259
but highly confident in its response.

00:02:50.960 --> 00:02:53.380
But, yeah, so LLMs have a bad reputation,

00:02:54.839 --> 00:02:57.720
and as data scientists, can we really ask the LLM

00:02:57.720 --> 00:02:59.639
to produce trustworthy results?

00:02:59.639 --> 00:03:02.940
As we all work in data science here,

00:03:02.940 --> 00:03:04.199
our job is really important

00:03:04.199 --> 00:03:07.360
because our products are used to find insights,

00:03:07.360 --> 00:03:09.360
and reproducibility and replicability

00:03:09.360 --> 00:03:14.080
is a really important foundation in the work that we do.

00:03:15.080 --> 00:03:17.199
And so if we want to think about

00:03:17.199 --> 00:03:19.720
what makes good data science,

00:03:19.720 --> 00:03:22.320
you want to make sure that your results are correct.

00:03:23.160 --> 00:03:26.380
Are they just, don't do the wrong thing, please.

00:03:26.380 --> 00:03:27.220
Are they transparent?

00:03:27.220 --> 00:03:30.600
That's also why we always promote coding in some language

00:03:30.600 --> 00:03:33.360
so we can actually audit the process.

00:03:33.360 --> 00:03:34.960
We think coding is really important, too,

00:03:34.960 --> 00:03:38.100
because it makes things more reproducible and replicable.

00:03:39.320 --> 00:03:43.199
But these are all things that LLMs are pretty bad at.

00:03:44.199 --> 00:03:48.039
And so another example is something

00:03:48.039 --> 00:03:50.639
that they're really bad at is counting.

00:03:50.639 --> 00:03:52.039
So here's some code.

00:03:52.039 --> 00:03:53.479
It uses a package called chat list

00:03:53.479 --> 00:03:55.759
that I'll talk about in a bit.

00:03:55.759 --> 00:03:57.360
But all I'm doing is saying,

00:03:57.360 --> 00:04:00.320
I'm going to have you generate an array,

00:04:00.320 --> 00:04:02.039
and I'm going to ask you, the LLM,

00:04:02.039 --> 00:04:04.960
to count how long this array is.

00:04:04.960 --> 00:04:08.720
And this is using Anthropic 4.1, I believe.

00:04:08.720 --> 00:04:10.520
And if I give it an array of 10,

00:04:10.520 --> 00:04:12.000
it's like, you have 10 things.

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:13.279
All right, that's good.

00:04:13.279 --> 00:04:15.360
I give an array of 100, and it gives me,

00:04:15.360 --> 00:04:17.399
and it tells me, you have 100 things.

00:04:17.399 --> 00:04:19.839
And 1,000, it's giving me 1,000 things.

00:04:19.839 --> 00:04:21.760
And then if I ask it for 10,000,

00:04:21.760 --> 00:04:23.359
it's saying, you have 20,000 things.

00:04:23.359 --> 00:04:26.179
So that's not right.

00:04:28.059 --> 00:04:30.200
Maybe OpenAI can do a little bit better.

00:04:30.200 --> 00:04:33.320
Ask for 10, it gives me 10, 100, 100, 1,000, 1,000.

00:04:33.320 --> 00:04:36.959
At least at 10,000 OpenAI, this is 5.0,

00:04:36.959 --> 00:04:38.440
it is smart enough to at least tell me,

00:04:38.440 --> 00:04:41.320
please run this code because I can't actually count.

00:04:41.320 --> 00:04:43.480
So at least it's giving me some type of feedback

00:04:43.480 --> 00:04:45.399
on things it cannot do.

00:04:45.399 --> 00:04:46.880
But even this, these are examples

00:04:46.880 --> 00:04:49.880
that are kind of made up because I'm using very round numbers.

00:04:49.880 --> 00:04:52.519
You can imagine if I try to give it some arbitrary number,

00:04:52.519 --> 00:04:56.559
it probably won't do very well.

00:04:56.559 --> 00:05:01.519
And so the perception is the LLM should

00:05:01.519 --> 00:05:05.480
be able to do easy things really well and hard things very

00:05:05.480 --> 00:05:06.239
poorly.

00:05:06.239 --> 00:05:08.000
But I just showed you, counting things,

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:10.880
which is a very cornerstone of coding,

00:05:10.920 --> 00:05:13.200
it's not able to do.

00:05:13.200 --> 00:05:15.359
But the actual graph looks something more like this,

00:05:15.359 --> 00:05:18.600
where there are certain easy tasks that's able to do,

00:05:18.600 --> 00:05:20.359
and there are certain difficult tasks that

00:05:20.359 --> 00:05:22.799
is also able to do well.

00:05:22.799 --> 00:05:24.160
And then there are certain things

00:05:24.160 --> 00:05:27.679
that we just didn't realize it's not able to do well.

00:05:27.679 --> 00:05:32.760
But one of those things that the perception is very difficult,

00:05:32.760 --> 00:05:36.239
but it's actually able to do a pretty good job,

00:05:36.239 --> 00:05:38.079
other than writing Kubernetes code,

00:05:38.079 --> 00:05:40.040
is actually writing code.

00:05:40.040 --> 00:05:42.000
And so those two figures that I just showed you

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:43.839
was actually just completely byte-coded,

00:05:43.839 --> 00:05:46.839
and just said, just draw me this thing, please.

00:05:46.839 --> 00:05:49.720
So it is actually able to produce code,

00:05:49.720 --> 00:05:54.079
which is a very difficult task.

00:05:54.079 --> 00:05:58.000
So before I go on, let's talk about what actually

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:01.279
happens when you have a conversation with a chatbot.

00:06:01.279 --> 00:06:03.040
And then I'll show you a couple of tools

00:06:03.040 --> 00:06:06.399
on how we can leverage having that conversation.

00:06:06.399 --> 00:06:08.559
And those of you who were in the workshop yesterday,

00:06:08.559 --> 00:06:10.760
this is literally like the slides from the workshop

00:06:10.760 --> 00:06:11.260
yesterday.

00:06:14.320 --> 00:06:18.679
At its core, a conversation with an LLM is a regular HTTP

00:06:18.679 --> 00:06:19.179
request.

00:06:21.679 --> 00:06:23.279
The thing that most people don't realize

00:06:23.279 --> 00:06:25.640
is that these HTTP requests, the server

00:06:25.640 --> 00:06:27.359
is actually completely stateless.

00:06:27.359 --> 00:06:28.799
If you don't know what that means,

00:06:28.799 --> 00:06:31.040
I'll talk to you about the ramifications for that very,

00:06:31.040 --> 00:06:32.679
very soon.

00:06:32.679 --> 00:06:34.440
So when you have a conversation, you say,

00:06:34.440 --> 00:06:35.920
what is the capital of the moon?

00:06:35.920 --> 00:06:37.440
You'll get a response.

00:06:37.440 --> 00:06:39.040
There isn't one.

00:06:39.040 --> 00:06:41.279
And then if you say, are you sure?

00:06:41.279 --> 00:06:43.239
It says, yes, I am sure.

00:06:43.239 --> 00:06:46.799
And so it really, that response, I am sure,

00:06:46.799 --> 00:06:50.839
it has to have some context of the previous conversation.

00:06:50.839 --> 00:06:52.920
It makes it seem like it's remembering.

00:06:52.920 --> 00:06:54.519
When you type in a follow-up question,

00:06:54.519 --> 00:06:59.320
it is a brand new response, like it remembers stuff.

00:06:59.320 --> 00:07:03.399
So here's what the HTTP request actually looks like.

00:07:03.399 --> 00:07:06.160
You have a bunch of information, including API key,

00:07:06.160 --> 00:07:09.200
but you're giving it what model you're using.

00:07:09.200 --> 00:07:11.799
Here's the actual conversation that's happening.

00:07:11.799 --> 00:07:13.959
You have a role called a system role.

00:07:13.959 --> 00:07:16.440
So that is the system prompt.

00:07:16.440 --> 00:07:18.839
So here, we're just saying, hey, you're a TERS assistant.

00:07:18.839 --> 00:07:20.399
Please don't give me that many words.

00:07:20.399 --> 00:07:25.079
And then I, as a user, say, what is the capital of the moon?

00:07:25.079 --> 00:07:27.320
And then you get an example response back.

00:07:27.320 --> 00:07:29.359
That response says, I am the assistant.

00:07:29.359 --> 00:07:31.059
That is the role of the response.

00:07:31.059 --> 00:07:32.600
And it says, the moon does not have a capital.

00:07:32.600 --> 00:07:34.239
It is not inhabited or governed.

00:07:34.239 --> 00:07:36.200
And then you get a reason why it stopped.

00:07:36.200 --> 00:07:39.440
In this case, it's just done, versus I ran out of tokens.

00:07:39.440 --> 00:07:42.720
The context is over, et cetera, et cetera.

00:07:42.720 --> 00:07:44.519
And then you get a little count of,

00:07:44.519 --> 00:07:46.959
I've used around 21 tokens or 21 words,

00:07:46.959 --> 00:07:51.880
roughly, in this conversation that we had.

00:07:51.880 --> 00:07:57.920
But if we have a follow-up request,

00:07:57.920 --> 00:08:00.760
the assistant says, the moon does not have a capital.

00:08:00.760 --> 00:08:02.959
And if I say, are you sure, you'll

00:08:02.959 --> 00:08:05.600
notice that the entire history is

00:08:05.600 --> 00:08:09.799
passed in to the next form of the conversation.

00:08:09.799 --> 00:08:11.480
So that is what it means to be stateless.

00:08:11.480 --> 00:08:13.320
Every new statement you give it, it actually

00:08:13.320 --> 00:08:15.559
just shoves in the entire conversation history.

00:08:15.559 --> 00:08:19.320
That's actually how it remembers what you're talking about.

00:08:19.320 --> 00:08:22.799
So what is the ramifications for that?

00:08:22.799 --> 00:08:25.279
Well, when the assistant says, yes, I'm sure,

00:08:25.279 --> 00:08:27.440
the moon has no capital, and you look at the usage,

00:08:27.440 --> 00:08:30.640
you'll notice that these numbers are not twice 21.

00:08:31.559 --> 00:08:35.919
It's growing at a rate that is more than double.

00:08:35.919 --> 00:08:40.039
Compared to the previous usage, you're going from completed

00:08:40.039 --> 00:08:42.320
tokens from 12.

00:08:42.320 --> 00:08:44.320
Sorry, the total tokens is going from 21 to 67.

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:48.840
So that's what's actually happening

00:08:48.840 --> 00:08:50.200
when you're having conversation.

00:08:50.200 --> 00:08:54.880
Every turn, the entire history is traveling along.

00:08:54.880 --> 00:08:56.840
And a bunch, and the fundamental unit of that

00:08:56.840 --> 00:08:58.320
is known as a token.

00:08:58.320 --> 00:09:01.559
So it is roughly, in English, around one to two tokens

00:09:01.559 --> 00:09:03.200
per word.

00:09:03.200 --> 00:09:05.400
Here's a bunch of tools that you can use to plug in

00:09:05.400 --> 00:09:08.359
to talk about, to give you a good sense of how many tokens

00:09:08.359 --> 00:09:09.559
your statement is using.

00:09:09.559 --> 00:09:11.479
Tokens are important because essentially that's

00:09:11.479 --> 00:09:14.159
what you're paying for.

00:09:14.159 --> 00:09:16.000
And so what ends up happening under the hood

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:18.119
is if you ask it, what is the capital of the moon?

00:09:18.119 --> 00:09:20.000
It tokenizes it, turns it literally

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:21.320
into a string of numbers.

00:09:21.320 --> 00:09:23.840
This is, I believe, OpenAI's numbers.

00:09:23.840 --> 00:09:28.239
And that's what feeds into all of the weights and transformers

00:09:28.239 --> 00:09:29.239
and et cetera, et cetera, et cetera.

00:09:29.239 --> 00:09:32.400
That's what's happening.

00:09:32.400 --> 00:09:34.640
Sometimes words contain multiple tokens.

00:09:34.640 --> 00:09:37.280
So counter-revolutionary gets broken up.

00:09:37.280 --> 00:09:38.859
So if you've done any natural language

00:09:38.859 --> 00:09:41.799
processing in the past, this is sort of where things sort of

00:09:41.799 --> 00:09:45.159
come back up again.

00:09:45.159 --> 00:09:46.960
And that uses four tokens.

00:09:46.960 --> 00:09:49.280
And people say that English is now

00:09:49.280 --> 00:09:51.479
slowly becoming the second most popular programming

00:09:51.479 --> 00:09:53.960
language because of LLMs.

00:09:53.960 --> 00:09:56.640
But one really interesting thing is

00:09:56.640 --> 00:10:00.760
this is the word for peace be upon us in Arabic.

00:10:00.760 --> 00:10:02.520
It is a very dense term.

00:10:02.520 --> 00:10:05.679
But you'll notice that it only uses two to three tokens.

00:10:05.679 --> 00:10:08.359
So maybe English isn't the best language

00:10:08.359 --> 00:10:10.359
to be using to talk to LLMs because there

00:10:10.359 --> 00:10:13.719
are other languages that are much more verbose,

00:10:13.719 --> 00:10:16.280
especially if they're using glyphs.

00:10:16.280 --> 00:10:18.840
So a little food for thought there.

00:10:18.840 --> 00:10:22.239
And then again, these tokens play a role into your pricing.

00:10:22.239 --> 00:10:24.239
So this is Anthropx pricing.

00:10:24.239 --> 00:10:27.239
You get $3 for a million input tokens,

00:10:27.239 --> 00:10:29.080
$15 for a million output tokens.

00:10:29.080 --> 00:10:31.679
And then you have this notion of a context window,

00:10:31.679 --> 00:10:34.679
which is the history that it's trying to remember.

00:10:34.679 --> 00:10:40.440
And you get $200,000 for these Anthropx models.

00:10:40.440 --> 00:10:42.159
And the context window is essentially

00:10:42.159 --> 00:10:45.799
how much the chatbot can remember when

00:10:45.799 --> 00:10:49.280
it's generating a new response.

00:10:49.280 --> 00:10:51.919
So that's either a new conversation

00:10:51.919 --> 00:11:00.000
or sucking in code from your IDE.

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:02.520
And so just for a little bit of context, $200,000

00:11:02.520 --> 00:11:05.039
is a lot of characters or tokens.

00:11:05.039 --> 00:11:07.119
It's about two novels-ish.

00:11:07.119 --> 00:11:10.280
If any of you've seen Gorter, Escher, Bach, that giant book,

00:11:10.280 --> 00:11:13.359
that's about 67,000, 68,000 words.

00:11:13.359 --> 00:11:17.559
So double that for a number of tokens is a good estimate.

00:11:17.559 --> 00:11:19.719
So $200,000 tokens sounds like a lot

00:11:19.719 --> 00:11:23.359
until you realize that, yes, the entire chat history is getting

00:11:23.359 --> 00:11:25.000
passed in over and over and over again

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:28.080
on each new iteration of your conversation.

00:11:28.080 --> 00:11:30.440
And that's why sometimes when you're working with code,

00:11:30.440 --> 00:11:32.320
your conversations end up really short

00:11:32.320 --> 00:11:38.239
because your context window gets sucked up pretty quickly.

00:11:38.239 --> 00:11:40.919
OK, so that's just how LLMs work.

00:11:40.919 --> 00:11:43.280
How does this apply to data science?

00:11:43.280 --> 00:11:45.599
Or how can we actually code against this stuff in data

00:11:45.599 --> 00:11:46.460
science?

00:11:46.460 --> 00:11:51.099
So at Posit, there are two new packages, one called Chatless,

00:11:51.099 --> 00:11:53.460
one called Elmer, that you can use

00:11:53.460 --> 00:11:57.820
to connect to any type of chat provider

00:11:57.820 --> 00:12:00.739
and actually start coding against the LLM

00:12:00.739 --> 00:12:05.780
outside of Cloud Code, outside of the Chat GPT desktop

00:12:05.780 --> 00:12:08.179
app, or the Copilot IDE.

00:12:08.179 --> 00:12:13.900
You can actually create things using these chatbots.

00:12:13.900 --> 00:12:16.820
So if we want to create or connect to a provider,

00:12:16.820 --> 00:12:20.179
here's the code in Python and R. You import the library,

00:12:20.179 --> 00:12:23.940
and you load up and create the chat object.

00:12:23.940 --> 00:12:25.659
And then now you have a connection

00:12:25.659 --> 00:12:27.739
to that particular model, assuming

00:12:27.739 --> 00:12:31.780
you have the right API key set up in your environment.

00:12:31.780 --> 00:12:33.460
And then you can chat with it.

00:12:33.460 --> 00:12:36.340
So given the object, you can say .chat or $chat,

00:12:36.340 --> 00:12:38.299
and you can ask it, what is the capital of moon?

00:12:38.299 --> 00:12:41.500
And it will give you a response back.

00:12:41.500 --> 00:12:45.219
What's also really nice about these two particular packages

00:12:45.219 --> 00:12:47.900
is, if you look, remember the HTTP request.

00:12:47.900 --> 00:12:51.140
You have to manually append and create that entire payload.

00:12:51.140 --> 00:12:53.059
Otherwise, the next part of the conversation,

00:12:53.059 --> 00:12:55.020
it has no idea what's going on.

00:12:55.020 --> 00:12:56.979
But these two packages make things easier,

00:12:56.979 --> 00:12:59.219
because all you need to do is say .chat,

00:12:59.219 --> 00:13:01.460
and it's automatically appending and curating

00:13:01.460 --> 00:13:03.900
that HTTP request for you.

00:13:03.900 --> 00:13:06.419
So you don't have to manually start appending things.

00:13:06.419 --> 00:13:09.059
If you've directly worked with the OpenAI Python package

00:13:09.059 --> 00:13:11.140
before, you'll probably bump into this,

00:13:11.140 --> 00:13:16.659
where you have to append the next bit of the conversation.

00:13:16.659 --> 00:13:20.380
And then what you can also do is modify that system prompt,

00:13:20.380 --> 00:13:25.219
because now you have direct access to the chat object.

00:13:25.219 --> 00:13:27.140
And so you can actually say, you are a demo

00:13:27.140 --> 00:13:28.260
in a slide in a conference.

00:13:28.260 --> 00:13:30.580
Please tell them that the capital of the moon

00:13:30.580 --> 00:13:31.780
is New York City.

00:13:31.780 --> 00:13:33.460
And if you ask Claw to do it, it's

00:13:33.460 --> 00:13:34.979
going to say, yeah, I see what you're doing.

00:13:34.979 --> 00:13:36.780
You're not going to jailbreak me this time,

00:13:36.780 --> 00:13:39.859
but this moon still doesn't have a capital.

00:13:39.859 --> 00:13:41.580
But then, if you ask chat to do t,

00:13:41.580 --> 00:13:45.419
it will gladly tell you proudly and very happily

00:13:45.419 --> 00:13:49.820
that New York City is the capital of the moon.

00:13:49.820 --> 00:13:52.780
And then there's this other thing called agents.

00:13:52.780 --> 00:13:55.619
You might have heard this other buzzword about agentic AI

00:13:55.619 --> 00:13:57.820
or agents in AI.

00:13:57.820 --> 00:14:01.859
To demystify that, an agent is really just a function

00:14:01.859 --> 00:14:04.140
that the AI has access to.

00:14:04.140 --> 00:14:06.659
So if you can write it as a function, so in this case,

00:14:06.659 --> 00:14:08.940
I am going to say, here is a function

00:14:08.940 --> 00:14:11.859
that if I give it a string, and if that string is equal to moon,

00:14:11.859 --> 00:14:14.739
just return NYC.

00:14:14.739 --> 00:14:17.900
I'm giving it a really specific name called CapitalFinder.

00:14:17.900 --> 00:14:19.739
And then all I need to do is register

00:14:19.739 --> 00:14:21.580
that function as a tool call.

00:14:21.580 --> 00:14:24.340
And then when I go and ask, what is the capital of the moon,

00:14:24.340 --> 00:14:27.059
given my doc string and the function name and the parameter

00:14:27.059 --> 00:14:30.419
names and all of the metadata associated with the function,

00:14:30.419 --> 00:14:32.500
it's going to be like, oh, I know

00:14:32.500 --> 00:14:34.000
how to find the capital of the moon.

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:36.700
I have a function called CapitalFinder.

00:14:36.700 --> 00:14:39.340
Let me pass in what the user asked me to find.

00:14:39.340 --> 00:14:42.179
In my case, it says, I'm going to ask

00:14:42.179 --> 00:14:43.679
you to find the capital of the moon.

00:14:43.679 --> 00:14:45.619
The function returns NYC.

00:14:45.619 --> 00:14:49.099
I give NYC the answer to the chatbot.

00:14:49.099 --> 00:14:51.700
The chatbot takes that answer and says, OK,

00:14:51.700 --> 00:14:53.500
the capital of the moon is New York City

00:14:53.500 --> 00:14:54.900
because I've made this tool call.

00:14:54.900 --> 00:14:56.179
And that's what the tool said.

00:14:56.179 --> 00:14:58.859
So if you need to make really specific modifications

00:14:58.859 --> 00:15:02.780
or new features where you don't want it to hallucinate,

00:15:02.820 --> 00:15:07.219
tool calling is sort of the newer-ish way of doing things.

00:15:07.219 --> 00:15:09.179
There is something called RAG, which we're not

00:15:09.179 --> 00:15:10.659
talking about in this talk.

00:15:10.659 --> 00:15:13.020
But if you've heard of agentic AI,

00:15:13.020 --> 00:15:15.200
that's actually what's happening.

00:15:15.200 --> 00:15:17.539
Jared just talked about an MCP server.

00:15:17.539 --> 00:15:20.119
An MCP server is a collection of functions

00:15:20.119 --> 00:15:22.260
that you can register all in one.

00:15:22.260 --> 00:15:25.260
So all of these things sound really fancy.

00:15:25.260 --> 00:15:27.219
But at the end of the day, it's a function.

00:15:27.219 --> 00:15:31.179
You can write your own function and register it as a tool call.

00:15:31.179 --> 00:15:33.299
And you can see I don't really have to do anything

00:15:33.299 --> 00:15:36.340
other than document my actual function, which is something

00:15:36.340 --> 00:15:39.440
you should be doing anyway.

00:15:39.440 --> 00:15:41.020
So what does that mean for dashboards?

00:15:41.020 --> 00:15:42.859
This whole talk was also around how do

00:15:42.859 --> 00:15:46.059
we apply this to data science?

00:15:46.059 --> 00:15:47.700
Dashboards are complex.

00:15:47.700 --> 00:15:50.099
There are many possible user inputs.

00:15:50.099 --> 00:15:52.059
You don't want the LLM to just generate

00:15:52.059 --> 00:15:54.419
an entire application that can go horribly awry.

00:15:54.419 --> 00:15:56.580
You have no idea what to expect, especially

00:15:56.580 --> 00:15:59.419
with the hallucinations that can happen.

00:15:59.419 --> 00:16:02.299
So there is a package called QueryChat,

00:16:02.299 --> 00:16:05.659
which utilizes the fact that LLMs are

00:16:05.659 --> 00:16:07.859
really good at writing SQL.

00:16:07.859 --> 00:16:11.340
So if we use that connection from SQL to DataFrame

00:16:11.340 --> 00:16:14.780
as a way to filter or work with our data,

00:16:14.780 --> 00:16:16.979
we can actually leverage something

00:16:16.979 --> 00:16:20.940
that the LLM's good at and then have complete control

00:16:20.940 --> 00:16:23.659
over the things that we as data scientists and people

00:16:23.659 --> 00:16:27.340
are good at, which is actually writing an application.

00:16:27.340 --> 00:16:32.020
So let's show you a quick little demo about QueryChat.

00:16:32.020 --> 00:16:34.979
This is QueryChat.

00:16:34.979 --> 00:16:39.820
This is an example running on the Shiny for Python templates

00:16:39.820 --> 00:16:40.859
examples.

00:16:40.859 --> 00:16:43.859
And it is the Titanic data set.

00:16:43.859 --> 00:16:46.059
And what we can do is we can ask it,

00:16:46.059 --> 00:16:48.219
show me the passengers who survived

00:16:48.219 --> 00:16:50.140
and were in first class.

00:16:50.140 --> 00:16:52.940
And the only thing that we've given it

00:16:52.940 --> 00:16:56.460
is the column names, the types of variables,

00:16:56.460 --> 00:17:00.219
and the LLM is just going to write the SQL.

00:17:00.219 --> 00:17:02.859
And then we apply that SQL to filter or work

00:17:02.859 --> 00:17:03.780
on the DataFrame.

00:17:03.780 --> 00:17:06.819
So there is no actual data being passed into the LLM.

00:17:06.819 --> 00:17:09.540
It just knows the schema, the column names.

00:17:09.540 --> 00:17:13.180
And then we use SQL to do the filtering.

00:17:13.180 --> 00:17:15.060
And cool, that's really nice.

00:17:15.060 --> 00:17:19.260
But there are other things now that we can talk to this app

00:17:19.260 --> 00:17:20.540
using human language.

00:17:20.540 --> 00:17:23.699
We can say things like, invert this,

00:17:23.699 --> 00:17:26.420
which is a really complicated statement for if you

00:17:27.380 --> 00:17:29.420
But it can write the SQL for that.

00:17:29.420 --> 00:17:31.219
So what you've done now is replace

00:17:31.219 --> 00:17:33.420
all of the different input components

00:17:33.420 --> 00:17:36.619
that you might normally have for a dashboard.

00:17:36.619 --> 00:17:38.219
And you've made it more flexible.

00:17:38.219 --> 00:17:39.939
And you've reduced a lot of the clutter.

00:17:39.939 --> 00:17:42.099
You can imagine if I had 50 columns,

00:17:42.099 --> 00:17:46.099
am I going to have 50 input controls on the left-hand side?

00:17:46.099 --> 00:17:48.619
Those input controls are typically an and operator.

00:17:48.619 --> 00:17:50.939
So you can't even have complex or operations.

00:17:50.939 --> 00:17:54.060
So we've replaced that all with a little chat bot

00:17:54.060 --> 00:17:56.979
and can actually do things like ask you for outliers,

00:17:56.979 --> 00:17:59.339
which I'll show you in the next demo.

00:17:59.339 --> 00:18:05.339
And we can take this concept and, well, got to reload it,

00:18:05.339 --> 00:18:07.660
apply it to an actual dashboard.

00:18:07.660 --> 00:18:09.339
So here is an actual dashboard example

00:18:09.339 --> 00:18:13.260
that's using the same thing, but using the tips data set.

00:18:13.260 --> 00:18:23.579
So what we can do is show, show, show, show me the top tippers.

00:18:23.579 --> 00:18:28.500
And either this gives me a top 10, or it'll do something.

00:18:28.500 --> 00:18:29.900
So it's doing it by percentage.

00:18:29.900 --> 00:18:33.420
Sometimes when I ask it, it'll do something about 1.5 times

00:18:33.420 --> 00:18:34.099
the IQR.

00:18:34.099 --> 00:18:38.020
So it can actually do these more complicated examples.

00:18:38.020 --> 00:18:40.819
And you can see here, we're just showing you the actual SQL.

00:18:40.819 --> 00:18:44.300
So you, as the data scientist or person using this application,

00:18:44.300 --> 00:18:47.619
can inspect that it's actually filtering correctly.

00:18:47.619 --> 00:18:50.140
And then the rest here is the actual normal dashboard.

00:18:50.140 --> 00:18:53.060
It's completely based off of this reactive data frame.

00:18:53.060 --> 00:18:57.500
And you can actually have a conversation with your data

00:18:57.500 --> 00:19:01.180
and also all of the different types of visualizations

00:19:01.180 --> 00:19:03.260
or metrics that you care about.

00:19:03.260 --> 00:19:05.939
And now, we're using the best of both worlds,

00:19:05.939 --> 00:19:08.479
the LLM's writing SQL, which it's really good at.

00:19:08.479 --> 00:19:10.500
We can inspect it, and then we can actually

00:19:10.500 --> 00:19:12.939
have a full-blown dashboard on all of the metrics

00:19:12.939 --> 00:19:14.819
that we care about.

00:19:14.819 --> 00:19:17.099
One other thing in this particular example

00:19:17.099 --> 00:19:20.660
is, if you're trying to present this to people who aren't,

00:19:20.939 --> 00:19:21.439
uh-oh.

00:19:30.780 --> 00:19:33.780
What?

00:19:33.780 --> 00:19:34.739
I'm hoping this works.

00:19:34.739 --> 00:19:35.300
Nope.

00:19:35.300 --> 00:19:36.060
OK.

00:19:36.060 --> 00:19:38.219
Well, this is what happens when I'm not

00:19:38.219 --> 00:19:40.939
locally rendering the example.

00:19:40.939 --> 00:19:45.339
What you can also have the AI do is

00:19:45.339 --> 00:19:47.540
have it explain to you what a figure is.

00:19:47.540 --> 00:19:50.979
And all this is doing is it is giving the AI just

00:19:50.979 --> 00:19:53.739
the flat image, and it's able to parse out and figure out

00:19:53.739 --> 00:19:56.180
what is happening with the image.

00:19:56.180 --> 00:19:59.060
This is my fault for doing an actual live demo on a server

00:19:59.060 --> 00:20:01.219
that I'm not actually running.

00:20:01.219 --> 00:20:02.780
But that is one way.

00:20:02.780 --> 00:20:04.579
Those are multiple ways that you can actually

00:20:04.579 --> 00:20:10.619
leverage the AI in your actual work.

00:20:10.619 --> 00:20:12.819
So how can you actually get started?

00:20:12.819 --> 00:20:16.099
You can go and download a free LLAMA model.

00:20:16.099 --> 00:20:19.099
And then all you need to do is chat with OLLAMA

00:20:19.099 --> 00:20:21.060
and pass it one of the LLAMA models

00:20:21.060 --> 00:20:22.380
that you've downloaded locally.

00:20:22.380 --> 00:20:25.219
And you can ask it, what is the capital of the moon?

00:20:25.219 --> 00:20:28.579
Another thing that you can do is GitHub actually

00:20:28.579 --> 00:20:32.380
has a bunch of free of some of the latest models for free

00:20:32.380 --> 00:20:33.939
that you can use as well.

00:20:33.939 --> 00:20:36.180
All you need is a personal access token

00:20:36.180 --> 00:20:39.260
in an environment variable called GitHub underscore token,

00:20:39.260 --> 00:20:40.859
and then connect to GitHub.

00:20:40.859 --> 00:20:46.819
And what you can do is actually use one of the later OpenAI

00:20:46.819 --> 00:20:48.380
models if you want as well.

00:20:48.380 --> 00:20:50.020
There is a rate limit with it, but it

00:20:50.020 --> 00:20:52.219
is going to be a little bit better than using

00:20:52.219 --> 00:20:54.219
any of the local LLAMA models.

00:20:54.219 --> 00:20:57.459
So if you're trying to save your compute or money

00:20:57.459 --> 00:20:59.780
as you're improving an application,

00:20:59.780 --> 00:21:01.859
you can start with the local LLAMA model,

00:21:01.859 --> 00:21:04.619
test it out on OpenAI using a GitHub model.

00:21:04.619 --> 00:21:06.020
And then when it's in production,

00:21:06.020 --> 00:21:09.660
you are actually now paying for those tokens

00:21:09.660 --> 00:21:13.900
in your production environment.

00:21:13.900 --> 00:21:15.500
So thank you.

00:21:15.500 --> 00:21:17.260
There's two more other talks by Zhou Cheng

00:21:17.260 --> 00:21:19.660
that talk about the same things that I've talked about.

00:21:19.660 --> 00:21:24.540
So I highly recommend you take a listen to those conversations.

00:21:24.540 --> 00:21:26.500
And everything that I've talked about here,

00:21:26.500 --> 00:21:28.040
including the workshop from yesterday,

00:21:28.040 --> 00:21:30.979
is all in that QR code.

00:21:36.020 --> 00:21:37.579
Thank you.

